data.content:
## What happened

This is a **C# 14 overload resolution breaking change** with span parameters. In .NET 10, the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so it throws at runtime.

## Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` so the compiler picks `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays (now binds to the in-place `Span` version). The fix pattern is identical: use `.AsEnumerable()` or call `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` explicitly.
